node.text:
I’m grateful for a day that celebrates running ✨ I’m sure this is the same for almost all of us, but to me, #globalrunningday means a lot more than mileage or just “being a runner”. Because when I think of running, I think of:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
•Running my first half marathon at age 20, after becoming a part of #metoo, failing out of nursing school, and having to move back home broken and destroyed. And I was different after that race.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
•Running my first full marathon at 27, when I was 8 months postpartum with our third child, in a broken body that did NOT look like a running model’s, and found a grit and a part of me that I never knew existed. And I was different after that race.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
•Running a Boston Qualifying time sometime in my 30’s, because I’m 5 days away from the big 3-0, and even though I’m a mother of 3 and have never been an athlete in my life, I AM qualifying for Boston. Soon. And I will be different after THAT race.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I love to run. I am a different person because of running. And I will continue to become a different person through running. It’s not my everything, but it has let me experience things and grow in ways that MEAN everything to me. With a grateful heart, I logged 7 miles of speedwork this morning (splits in stories). Happy Global Running Day to my beautiful running community! Lots of love to each of you today 🤗💛
